I looked for simple structure consistent with all positives and excluding negatives. All positive examples (besides empty) can be segmented into 6-character blocks, and in every such block:
- position 1 is a or b,
- position 2 is b or c,
- position 3 is a or c,
- position 4 is a,
- position 5 is b or c,
- position 6 is any of a, b, c.

This also rejects all provided negatives. Hence the language is the Kleene star over that 6-length pattern, which includes the empty string.

<ans>((a+b) (b+c) (a+c) a (b+c) (a+b+c))*</ans>

I looked for consistent structural patterns distinguishing positives from negatives. All positive strings either are exactly "c" or start with "c" and then consist of a concatenation of 5-character blocks. Each block is formed by a 2-letter prefix from {aa, ab, ac, ca, cb, cc} followed by one of the suffixes "abc" or "acc". This explains why "ccacc" (length 5) is negative (it’s not c + a full 5-letter block) while "cccacc" (c + "ccacc") is positive, and matches all other examples.
